# check how all categorical  features are distributed.

cat_cols= ['sex','cp','fbs','restecg','exang','slope','ca','thal']

plt.figure(figsize=(10,len(cat_cols)*5))

for i,val in enumerate(cat_cols):
  #print( i.__str__() +'  ' + val)
  plt.subplot(len(cat_cols), 1, i+1)
  df_plot= df.groupby([val,'target'])["target"].count().reset_index(name="count")
  df_plot=df_plot.round(decimals = 2)
  df_plot=df_plot.pivot(val, "target", "count")
  df_plot.reset_index(inplace=True)
  ax=df_plot.plot(x=val, y=[0, 1], kind="bar",logy=False,logx=False,ax=plt.gca(),fontsize = 10,alpha=0.75, rot=10,sort_columns = True)
  for p in ax.patches:
    ax.annotate('{:}'.format(p.get_height()), (p.get_x()+p.get_width()/2, p.get_height()))
  plt.title( val +' vs target',fontsize = 20, color='Navy')
  plt.legend(fontsize = 10)
  plt.xlabel(val,fontsize = 0)
  plt.ylabel('count',fontsize = 10)

3.2.2 Feature Engineering Technique - Chi Square¶

Since the data set comprises of categorical values, have used the chi square test. The chi-square value is calculated between each attribute and the target variable, and the attributes with the best chi-square value is selected.

In [12]:
from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectKBest
from sklearn.feature_selection import chi2

features=list(df.columns)
features.remove('target')

x = df.loc[:, features].values
# Separating out the target
y = df.loc[:,['target']].values

# Standardizing the features

chi_scores = chi2(x,y)
In [13]:
df_chi=pd.DataFrame(chi_scores)
df_chi.columns=features
df_chi_scores=df_chi.transpose()
df_chi_scores['features'] = df_chi_scores.index
df_chi_scores.columns=['Chi_Square', 'P_Value','Features']
df_chi_scores = df_chi_scores.reset_index(drop=True)
df_chi_scores= df_chi_scores.sort_values('P_Value')
print(df_chi_scores)

3.2.3 Feature Engineering --Random Forest Classifier

Random forest classifier techinique uses multiple decision trees and merges them together to form a precise and stable prediction for a larger data set.

In [15]:
#Check feature importance
from sklearn import ensemble
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

##Get list of features which will be used to predict 'subs_deposit'. 
featured_cols= list(df.columns)
col_names= featured_cols
col_names.remove('target')


##Use model RandomForestRegressor to see feature importance to predict target 'subs_deposit'
model=ensemble.RandomForestClassifier()
#fit the model with train data
model.fit(df[col_names],df['target'])
importances = model.feature_importances_
idxs = np.argsort(importances)
plt.title("Feature Importances")
plt.barh(range(len(idxs)), importances[idxs], align='center')
plt.yticks(range(len(idxs)), [col_names[i] for i in idxs])
plt.xlabel("Random Forest Feature Importance")
plt.show()

As per Random forest, important features are 'cp','ca','oldpeak','thalach','thal','age','chol','trestbps','exang','slope'

features=list(df.columns)
features.remove('target')

x = df.loc[:, features].values
# Separating out the target
y = df.loc[:,['target']].values

# Perform dimension reduction by PCA and project it to 2 dimensions.
pca = PCA(n_components=2)
principalComponents = pca.fit_transform(x)
principalDf = pd.DataFrame(data = principalComponents
             , columns = ['pc1', 'pc2'])
finalDf = pd.concat([principalDf, df.target],axis=1)

4.1 Split the dataset into training and test sets. Justify your choice of split. You may experiment with different split to get the final split¶

We have taken train/test split as 80/20 and 60/40.
The higher training data set percentage gives more accurate results.
We observed that the higher percentage of training data (70-80%) gives a more accurate result.

Split1--> 80:20 split. 80% of data will be used for training and 20% of data will be used for testing.

classifier = KNeighborsClassifier()

k_range = list(range(1, 31))
param_grid = dict(n_neighbors=k_range)

#initialize grid serach
model=model_selection.GridSearchCV(
    estimator=classifier,
    param_grid=param_grid,
    scoring="accuracy",
    verbose=1,
    n_jobs=1,
    cv=5
)

#fit the model 

model.fit(x_train, y_train.ravel())
print(f"Best score: {model.best_score_}")
print("Best Parameter set:")
best_parameters=model.best_estimator_.get_params()

  print(f"\t {param_name}: {best_parameters[param_name]}")

5.2 Conclusion:¶

Since we are getting best accuracy with KNN using case1 where model is trained on 80% dataset and 20% used for testing. We are getting accuracy of 100%, which is highest. KNN is the preferred model for this dataset. Train Test split of 80:20 is preferred.
